  <datafield tag="245" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Electromagnetic triangle anomaly and neutral pion condensation in QCD vacuum</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="260" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="c">2016-06-10</subfield>
    <subfield code="t">published</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="300" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">5</subfield>
  </datafield>
  <datafield tag="520" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">We study the QCD vacuum structure under the influence of an electromagnetic field with a nonzero second Lorentz invariant <math altimg="si1.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">E</mi><mo>⋅</mo><mi mathvariant="bold-italic">B</mi></math> . We show that the presence of <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> can induce neutral pion ( <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>π</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msup></math> ) condensation in the QCD vacuum through the electromagnetic triangle anomaly. Within the frameworks of chiral perturbation theory at leading small-momenta expansion as well as the Nambu–Jona-Lasinio model at leading <math altimg="si4.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">/</mo><msub><mrow><mi>N</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>c</mi></mrow></msub></math> expansion, we quantify the dependence of the <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>π</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msup></math> condensate on <math altimg="si2.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msub><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msub></math> . The stability of the <math altimg="si3.gif" display="inline" overflow="scroll"><msup><mrow><mi>π</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msup></math> -condensed vacuum against the Schwinger charged pair production due to electric field is also discussed.</subfield>
    <subfield code="9">Elsevier</subfield>
  </datafield>
